lilac is an extremely powerful programming language tailored specifically for
the lavender operating system. it provides low-level system control with minimal
handholding like c, while also integrating tightly with the apis and systems of
lavender. its syntax is extremely easy to understand, and the full suite of
tools that come with its command-line management interface (built into
lavender!) provide a rich ecosystem that will rarely leave you wanting for extra
features.

this starting tutorial will teach you both the basics and the advanced portions
of the language, and then run through some shorter tutorials for how to build
things like graphical applications and even system modules. this tutorial is
available both online at the [<link:"https://sermir.online/learning/lilac">
sermir website] and offline in lavender's manual library.

before we begin this tutorial, we should set up the development environment. for
this, you are going to need three lavender utilities; `new`, `enter`, and
`lilac`. the usage of the `new` command is easy to understand if you've used
lavender for any stretch of time, we're going to use it to create a lilac
project. run the following code in the terminal (you can bring up a new one via
[<key> meta+t]):.

[<code:terminal>
new lilac project called "hello_lilac"
enter $code
]

that [<ref> enter $code] command just changes the working directory to the
system-wide code directory, which is where the new lilac project will have been
created. the project will look like this if you [<ref> list here]:

[<code:directory>
.
|- sources
|--|- entry
|--|- build
|- project
|- copying
|- roadmap
]

the [<ref> roadmap] file just contains a single roadmap item in standard lilac
todo format; "implement project! :)". this is here for your personal usage, but
it isn't a required file, and therefore can be deleted if you wish. the
[<ref> project] file just contains the name of your project right now, but is
the "readme" document for this project. this can contain whatever you wish. the
[<ref> copying] file contains the license for this project, by default the
[<link:"https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.txt"> gplv3]. this can be
changed to whatever you wish.

the [<ref> sources] directory will contain sources for your lilac project. by
default, the entry point (the function to be executed first in your program) and
the build script (the file the compiler will use to customize the build process
for your specific project) are the only things in this directory. the build
script must be named as it is in this folder ([<ref> build.lilac]), but the
entry point can be named whatever you'd like, so long as it's referenced as the
same name in the build script.

you now have a lilac project! that's the full lilac project management
experience, minus source control which we will get into in a much later chapter.
